{"title_page": "Mary Noble", "text_new": "{{for2|the judge in Kentucky|[[Mary C. Noble]]|the American radio soap opera|''[[Backstage Wife]]''}}\n{{Short description|Scottish seed pathologist}}\nDr '''Mary Jessie MacDonald Noble''' [[FRSE]] FIB [[Imperial Service Order|ISO]] (23 February 1911 \u2013 20 July 2002) was a seed pathologist for the Department of Agriculture for Scotland and was key in producing the ''Handbook of Seed-borne Diseases''.\n\n==Life==\nShe was born in [[Edinburgh]] the daughter of John Noble a pharmacist on Gladstone Place on [[Leith Links]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/dr-mary-noble-1-615957|title=Dr Mary Noble|publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> The family lived at 37 Willowbrae Road.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1911</ref>\n\nShe was educated privately at the [[The Mary Erskine School|Mary Erskine School]] and went on to study Botany at the [[University of Edinburgh]] from 1920\u20131935, under Dr [[Malcolm Wilson (botanist)|Malcolm Wilson]], where she earned an honours degree in botany. She then earned a PhD on the mycological aspects of seed pathology.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zs6qBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA284&lpg=PA284&dq=Mary+Jessie+McDonald+Noble&source=bl&ots=FXEMBgEwh5&sig=LevH6r_xHd9NHKwIV9-VX2-Etos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidmYWbn73PAhViAsAKHbxDCZ0Q6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Jessie%20McDonald%20Noble&f=false|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Scottish Women|last=Ewan|first=Elizabeth L.|last2=Innes|first2=Sue|last3=Reynolds|first3=Sian|last4=Pipes|first4=Rose|date=2006-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748626601|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter university, she joined the plant pathology service of the Board of Agriculture (now known as SASA) based in the Royal Botanic Gardens, Edinburgh. In Noble's career on plant pathology, seeds were her main focus. In 1958 she was elected as Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (one of the few female Fellows). Her proposers were [[Malcolm Wilson (botanist)|Malcolm Wilson]], [[Charles Edward Foister]], John Anthony and Sir [[William Wright Smith]]. She won the Society's Gunning Victoria Jubilee Prize.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf|access-date=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074135/https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAs well as becoming a Fellow, she also served as a councillor for [[British Mycological Society]] and the [[Association of Applied Biologists]]. She was also a member of the International Seed Testing Association and, along with Dr Paul Neergaard and Dr Jo deTempe, produced an ''Annotated List of Seed-borne Diseases (4th edition, ISTA , 1990).'' In 1971, she retired as principle scientific officer for seed pathology and mycology at the Agriculture Scientific Society for the Department of Agriculture and Fisheries for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/dr-mary-noble-1-615957|title=Dr Mary Noble|website=www.scotsman.com|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref>\n\nNoble retired in 1971 and died on 20 July 2002 in [[Lasswade]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/obits_alpha/noble_mary.pdf|title=Mary Jessie MacDonald Noble|last=Watling|first=Roy|date=|website=Royal Society of Edinburgh|publisher=|access-date=8 Dec 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noble, Mary Jessie MacDonald}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish biologists]]\n[[Category:British women biologists]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Imperial Service Order]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Scottish seed pathologist}}\n{{for2|the judge in Kentucky|[[Mary C. Noble]]|the American radio soap opera|''[[Backstage Wife]]''}}\nDr '''Mary Jessie MacDonald Noble''' [[FRSE]] FIB [[Imperial Service Order|ISO]] (23 February 1911 \u2013 20 July 2002) was a seed pathologist for the Department of Agriculture for Scotland and was key in producing the ''Handbook of Seed-borne Diseases''.\n\n==Life==\nShe was born in [[Edinburgh]] the daughter of John Noble a pharmacist on Gladstone Place on [[Leith Links]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/dr-mary-noble-1-615957|title=Dr Mary Noble|publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref> The family lived at 37 Willowbrae Road.<ref>Edinburgh Post Office Directory 1911</ref>\n\nShe was educated privately at the [[The Mary Erskine School|Mary Erskine School]] and went on to study Botany at the [[University of Edinburgh]] from 1920\u20131935, under Dr [[Malcolm Wilson (botanist)|Malcolm Wilson]], where she earned an honours degree in botany. She then earned a PhD on the mycological aspects of seed pathology.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zs6qBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA284&lpg=PA284&dq=Mary+Jessie+McDonald+Noble&source=bl&ots=FXEMBgEwh5&sig=LevH6r_xHd9NHKwIV9-VX2-Etos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidmYWbn73PAhViAsAKHbxDCZ0Q6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=Mary%20Jessie%20McDonald%20Noble&f=false|title=The Biographical Dictionary of Scottish Women|last=Ewan|first=Elizabeth L.|last2=Innes|first2=Sue|last3=Reynolds|first3=Sian|last4=Pipes|first4=Rose|date=2006-03-08|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748626601|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter university, she joined the plant pathology service of the Board of Agriculture (now known as SASA) based in the Royal Botanic Gardens, Edinburgh. In Noble's career on plant pathology, seeds were her main focus. In 1958 she was elected as Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (one of the few female Fellows). Her proposers were [[Malcolm Wilson (botanist)|Malcolm Wilson]], [[Charles Edward Foister]], John Anthony and Sir [[William Wright Smith]]. She won the Society's Gunning Victoria Jubilee Prize.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0 902 198 84 X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf|access-date=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074135/https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAs well as becoming a Fellow, she also served as a councillor for [[British Mycological Society]] and the [[Association of Applied Biologists]]. She was also a member of the International Seed Testing Association and, along with Dr Paul Neergaard and Dr Jo deTempe, produced an ''Annotated List of Seed-borne Diseases (4th edition, ISTA , 1990).'' In 1971, she retired as principle scientific officer for seed pathology and mycology at the Agriculture Scientific Society for the Department of Agriculture and Fisheries for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/dr-mary-noble-1-615957|title=Dr Mary Noble|website=www.scotsman.com|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref>\n\nNoble retired in 1971 and died on 20 July 2002 in [[Lasswade]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/obits_alpha/noble_mary.pdf|title=Mary Jessie MacDonald Noble|last=Watling|first=Roy|date=|website=Royal Society of Edinburgh|publisher=|access-date=8 Dec 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noble, Mary Jessie MacDonald}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish biologists]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:People from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Imperial Service Order]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Noble"}
{"title_page": "Billboard Music Award", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = ''Billboard'' Music Awards\n| current_awards = 2019 Billboard Music Awards\n| image          = Billboard-music-awards-logo.png\n| imagesize      = 200px\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| description    = Outstanding chart performance\n| presenter      = [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]\n| country        = United States\n| network        = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (1990\u20132006)<br />[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (2011\u20132017)<br />[[NBC]] (2018\u2013present)\n| year           = {{start date and age|1990|12|10}}\n| website        = {{URL|billboardmusicawards.com}}\n}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Most recent ''Billboard'' Music Award winners\n| election_date = [[2019 Billboard Music Awards|May 1, 2019]]\n| type = primary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2018 Billboard Music Awards\n| previous_year = 2018\n| next_election =\n| next_year = 2020\n| opinion_polls = \n| 1blank = Award\n| 2blank = Winner\n| image1 = [[File:Drake_at_The_Carter_Effect_2017_(36818935200)_(cropped).jpg|160x160px]]\n| 1data1 = [[Billboard Music Award for Top Artist|Top Artist]] & [[Billboard Music Award for Top Male Artist|Top Male Artist]]\n| 2data1 = [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| image2 = [[File:Dangerous Woman Tour in Manchester4 (cropped).jpg|160x160px]]\n| 1data2 = [[Billboard Music Award for Top Female Artist|Top Female Artist]]\n| 2data2 = [[Ariana Grande]]\n| image4 = [[File:Drake_at_The_Carter_Effect_2017_(36818935200)_(cropped).jpg|160x160px]]\n| 1data4 = [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Top ''Billboard'' 200 Album]]\n| 2data4 = [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]<br/>(''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]'')\n| image5 = [[File:AdamLevine2011.jpg|160x160px]]\n| 1data5 = [[Billboard Music Award for Top Hot 100 Song|Top Hot 100 Song]]\n| 2data5 = [[Maroon 5]] featuring [[Cardi B]]<br/>(\"[[Girls Like You]]\")\n| title = Top Artist\n| before_election = [[Ed Sheeran]]\n| after_election = [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| 1data3 = [[Billboard Music Award for Top New Artist|Top New Artist]]\n| 2data3 = [[Juice Wrld]]\n| image3 = [[File:Juice Wrld Interview.png|160x160px]]\n}}\nThe '''''Billboard'' Music Award''' is an honor given out annually by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', a publication and [[Billboard charts|music popularity chart]] covering the music business. The ''Billboard'' Music Awards show had been held annually since 1990 and the event was formerly held in December<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7386047/top-billboard-music-award-winners-all-time-1990-2016 |title=Top Billboard Music Award Winners of All Time (1990\u20132016) |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |date=March 31, 2016 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> until it went dormant in 2006. The awards returned in 2011 and are now held annually in May.\n\n==Awards process==\nUnlike other awards, such as the [[Grammy Award]], which determine nominations as a result of the highest votes received by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]], the ''Billboard'' Music Awards finalists are based on album and digital songs sales, streaming, radio airplay, touring, and social engagement. These measurements are tracked year-round by ''Billboard'' and its data partners, including [[Nielsen SoundScan|\nNielsen Music]] and [[Next Big Sound]]. The 2018 awards are based on the reporting period of April 8, 2017 through March 31, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8343598/billboard-music-awards-2018-nominations-list |title=Billboard Music Awards 2018 Nominations: See the Full List |date=April 17, 2018 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> Awards are given for the top album, artist and single in a number of different [[music genres]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:95%; width:100%; text-align:center\"\n|-\