owspan=\"3\"| [[NBC]]\n| [[Ed Sheeran]]\n| [[Ed Sheeran]]\n| [[Taylor Swift]]\n| [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]]\n| [[Imagine Dragons]]\n| \"[[Despacito]]\"<br>[[Luis Fonsi]] and [[Daddy Yankee]] {{small|(feat. [[Justin Bieber]])}}\n| ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|DAMN]]''<br>[[Kendrick Lamar]]\n| [[Ed Sheeran]] and [[Kendrick Lamar]]<br>{{small|(6 awards)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]], [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8094432/billboard-music-awards-2018-date|title=Billboard Music Awards 2018 Date Announced|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|date=January 16, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 26\n| [[2019 Billboard Music Awards|2019]]\n| [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| [[Ariana Grande]]\n| [[Juice Wrld]]\n| [[BTS (band)|BTS]]\n| \"[[Girls Like You]]\"<br>[[Maroon 5]] {{small|(feat. [[Cardi B]])}}\n| ''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]'' - [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n| [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]<br>{{small|(12 awards)}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8509655/billboard-music-awards-2019-winners-list|title=2019 Billboard Music Awards Winners: The Complete List|website=Billboard|date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 27\n| 2020<ref>{{cite web|title=\"2020 Billboard Music Awards\" Will Broadcast Live from the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas on Wednesday, April 29 at 8 P.M. ET on NBC|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2019/08/12/2020-billboard-music-awards-will-broadcast-live-from-the-mgm-grand-garden-arena-in-las-vegas-on-wednesday-april-29-at-8-pm-et-on-nbc-527513/20190812nbc02/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| {{TBA}}\n| \n|}\n*{{small|Whitney Houston won the award for \"#1 World Artist\".<ref name=\"1993 awards\"/> This field shows winners of \"Artist of the Year\" (awarded from 1995 to 2006), and \"Top Artist\" (awarded since 2011).}}\n\n==Categories==\nFrom 1989 to 2006, the show had the same categories and category names every year. In 2011, for the first time, all of the awards were renamed to \"Top [award title]\". The \"of the year\" portion of each category title no longer exists, and many of the awards have been further renamed. Other awards, including both \"crossover\" awards (No. 1 Classical Crossover Artist and No. 1 Classical Crossover Album) were discontinued. As of 2017, there are two fan-voted categories.\n\n===Current categories===\nThe general categories are Top Artist, Top Billboard 200 Album, Top Hot 100 Song and Top New Artist. These categories highlighted in each award and other categories are divided by genre.\n\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Artist|Top Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top New Artist|Top New Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Male Artist|Top Male Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Female Artist|Top Female Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Duo/Group|Top Duo/Group]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Artist|Top ''Billboard 200'' Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Top ''Billboard 200'' Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Hot 100 Artist|Top Hot 100 Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Hot 100 Song|Top Hot 100 Song]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Touring Artist|Top Touring Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Song Sales Artist|Top Song Sales Artist]] (since 2016)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Selling Album|Top Selling Album]] (since 2018)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Selling Song|Top Selling Song]] (since 2016)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Radio Songs Artist|Top Radio Songs Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Radio Song|Top Radio Song]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Streaming Artist|Top Streaming Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Streaming Song (Audio)|Top Streaming Song (Audio)]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Streaming Song (Video)|Top Streaming Song (Video)]]\n*Top Collaboration (since 2017)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top R&B Artist|Top R&B Artist]]\n*Top R&B Male Artist (since 2018)\n*Top R&B Female Artist (since 2018)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top R&B Album|Top R&B Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top R&B Song|Top R&B Song]]\n*Top R&B Tour (2017 \u2013 present)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Artist|Top Rap Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Male Artist|Top Rap Male Artist]] (since 2018)\n*[[Billboard Music Award Top Rap Female Artist|Top Rap Female Artist]] (since 2018)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Album|Top Rap Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Song|Top Rap Song]]\n*Top Rap Tour (since 2017)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Country Artist|Top Country Artist]]\n*Top Country Male Artist (since 2018)\n*Top Country Female Artist (since 2018)\n*Top Country Duo/Group Artist (since 2018)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Country Album|Top Country Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Country Song|Top Country Song]]\n*Top Country Tour (since 2017)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rock Artist|Top Rock Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rock Album|Top Rock Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rock Song|Top Rock Song]]\n*Top Rock Tour (since 2017)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Latin Artist|Top Latin Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Latin Album|Top Latin Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Latin Song|Top Latin Song]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Dance/Electronic Artist|Top Dance/Electronic Artist]] (since 2014)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Dance/Electronic Album|Top Dance/Electronic Album]] (since 2014)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Dance/Electronic Song|Top Dance/Electronic Song]] (since 2014)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Christian Artist|Top Christian Artist]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Christian Album|Top Christian Album]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Christian Song|Top Christian Song]]\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Gospel Artist|Top Gospel Artist]] (since 2016)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Gospel Album|Top Gospel Album]] (since 2016)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Gospel Song|Top Gospel Song]] (since 2016)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Soundtrack|Top Soundtrack]] (1993, 1998, 2000, 2006, 2015 \u2013 present)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Social Artist|Top Social Artist]] (fan voted)\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Chart Achievement|''Billboard'' Chart Achievement]] (since 2015, fan-voted)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Retired categories (1990\u20132017)===\n\n{{Div col}}\n*Top Alternative Album\n*Top Alternative Artist\n*Top Alternative Song\n*Top Classical Crossover Artist\n*Top Classical Crossover Album\n*Top Country Collaboration (2017)\n*Top Dance Artist (until 2013)\n*Top Dance Album (until 2013)\n*Top Dance Song (until 2013)\n*Top Digital Media Artist (until 2012)\n*Top Digital Songs Artist (until 2015)\n*Top Digital Song (until 2015)\n*Top EDM Artist (until 2013)\n*Top EDM Album (until 2013)\n*Top EDM Song (until 2013)\n*Top Independent Artists\n*Top Independent Album\n*Top Modern Rock Artist\n*Top Modern Rock Track\n*Top New Male Artist\n*Top New Female Artist\n*Top New Group/Band\n*Top New Song\n*Top Pop Song (until 2013)\n*Top Pop Album (until 2013)\n*Top Pop Artist (until 2013)\n*Top Pop Punk Artist\n*[[Billboard Music Award for Top Rap Artist|Top Rap Artist]] (until 2017)\n*Top R&B Collaboration (2017)\n*Top Rap Collaboration (2017)\n*Top Rhythmic Top 40 Title\n*Top Selling Single\n*Top Soundtrack Single of the Year\n*Milestone Award (2013, 2014)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Special awards===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Artist Achievement Award====\n* 1993: [[Rod Stewart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/12/08/Whitney-Houston-big-winner-at-Billboard-Music-Awards/2652755326800/|title=1993 Billboard Music Awards|date=December 8, 1993 |work=Billboard Music Awards|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref>\n* 1995: [[Janet Jackson]]\n* 1996: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n* 1997: [[Garth Brooks]]\n* 1999: [[Aerosmith]]\n* 2001: [[Janet Jackson]]\n* 2002: [[Cher]]\n* 2004: [[Destiny's Child]]\n* 2005: [[Kanye West]]<ref>{{cite\n* 2003: [[Kyalsan Blokber]]\nweb|url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/2016/04/won-artist-achievement-award/|title=Who Has Won the Artist Achievement Award?|date=12 April 2016|work=Billboard Music Awards|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Millennium Award====\n* 2011: [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n* 2012: [[Whitney Houston]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/whitney-houston-1963-2012/news/a381956/whitney-houston-to-receive-posthumous-billboard-millennium-award/ |title=Whitney Houston to Receive The Billboard Millennium Award |work=Digital Spy| date=May 16, 2012 | accessdate=May 20, 2014 |author=Harp, Justin}}</ref> <small>(award accepted by her daughter, [[Bobbi Kristina Brown]])</small>\n* 2016: [[Britney Spears]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7350405/britney-spears-billboard-millenium-award-honoree | title=Britney Spears to Perform Hits Medley at Billboard Music Awards | work=Billboard | date=May 2, 2016 | accessdate=May 2, 2016 | author=Melendez, Monique}}</ref>\n\n====Century Award====\n* 1992: [[George Harrison]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=century-award | title=Winners Database: Century Award| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n* 1993: [[Buddy Guy]]\n* 1994: [[Billy Joel]]\n* 1995: [[Joni Mitchell]]\n* 1996: [[Carlos Santana]]\n* 1997: [[Chet Atkins]]\n* 1998: [[James Taylor]]\n* 1999: [[Emmylou Harris]]\n* 2000: [[Randy Newman]]\n* 2001: [[John Mellencamp]]\n* 2002: [[Annie Lennox]]\n* 2003: [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]\n* 2004: [[Stevie Wonder]]\n* 2005: [[Tom Petty]]\n* 2006: [[Tony Bennett]]\n\n====Icon Award====\n{{Main|Billboard Icon Award}}\n*2011: [[Neil Diamond]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/471529/neil-diamond-accepts-billboard-icon-award-closes-bbmas-with-sweet-medley|title=Neil Diamond|date=23 May 2011|work=Billboard|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2012: [[Stevie Wonder]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1097020/stevie-wonder-to-receive-icon-award-at-billboard-music-awards|title=Stevie Wonder to Receive Icon Award at Billboard Music Awards|date=8 May 2012|work=Billboard|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2013: [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2013/1510642/prince-to-be-honored-at-billboard-music-awards-on-may-19|title=Prince|date=18 January 2013|work=Billboard|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2014: [[Jennifer Lopez]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2014/6092051/jennifer-lopez-icon-award-billboard-music-awards|title=Jennifer Lopez|date=19 May 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2016: [[Celine Dion]]<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7356823/celine-dion-icon-award-perform-2016-billboard-music-awards]</ref>\n*2017: [[Cher]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7784307/billboard-music-awards-2017-cher-icon-award|title=Cher to Receive Icon Award at 2017 Billboard Music Awards|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n*2018: [[Janet Jackson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8454737/janet-jackson-receiving-icon-award-bbmas-2018|title=Janet Jackson to Receive Icon Award at 2018 Billboard Music Awards|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n*2019: [[Mariah Carey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/8506708/mariah-carey-icon-award-2019-billboard-music-awards|title=Mariah Carey to Receive Icon Award at 2019 Billboard Music Awards|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n*2020: [[Garth Brooks]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/bbma/8551898/garth-brooks-icon-award-2020-billboard-music-awards|title=Garth Brooks Is an Icon & Soon He\u2019ll Have The Billboard Music Award to Prove it|website=billboard.com}}</ref>\n\n====Spotlight Award====\nIn 1988, [[Michael Jackson]] was honored with ''Billboard''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s first [[Billboard Music Award for Spotlight|Spotlight Award]] for being the first artist in music history to have five consecutive number ones singles on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] from [[Bad (album)|one album]]. In 2012, [[Katy Perry]] was honored with ''Billboard''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s second Spotlight award for being the second and first female artist in music history to have five consecutive number ones singles on ''Billboard'' Hot 100 from [[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry album)|one album]].\n\n====Other special awards====\n*1992: Special Award commemorating the 10th Anniversary of ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'': [[Michael Jackson]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=special-award-commemorating-the-10th-anniversary-of-thriller | title=Winners Database: 10th Anniversary of \"Thriller\"| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*1992: No. 1 World Album for ''[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]'' and No. 1 World Single for \"[[Black or White]]\": [[Michael Jackson]]\n*1993: Special Award for the first single with most weeks at No.1 on the Billboard Hot 100 (14 weeks for \"[[I Will Always Love You#Whitney Houston version|I Will Always Love You]]\"): [[Whitney Houston]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=whitney+houston&winnerYear=1993&winnerCategory=single-with-most-weeks-at-1|title=Winners Database: Special Award for the first Single with most weeks at No.1 on the Billboard Hot 100| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*1996: Special Award for most weeks at No. 1 on the Billboard Hot 100 (16 weeks for \"[[One Sweet Day]]\"): [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Boyz II Men]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=special-hot-100-singles-award-most-weeks-at-no-1-on-the-billboard-hot-100-16-weeks-for-one-sweet-day| title=Winners Database: Special Award for most weeks at No. 1 on The Billboard Hot 100| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*1997: Special Award honoring \"[[Candle In the Wind 1997]]\" as the all-time best selling single: [[Elton John]] and [[Bernie Taupin]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=special-billboard-award-honoring-candle-in-the-wind-1997-as-the-all-time-best-selling-single | title=Winners Database: Special Billboard Award (Honoring \"Candle In the Wind 1997\" as the all-time best selling single)| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*1998: Special Award for the most No. 1s ever by a female artist (13): [[Mariah Carey]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=special-billboard-hot-100-award-for-the-most-no-1s-ever-by-a-female-artist-13 | title=Winners Database: Special Award for the most No. 1s ever by a female artist| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*2000: Special Award for biggest one-week sales ever of an album: ''[[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]'', [[NSYNC]]<ref name=\"2000bmas\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/sisqo-destinys-child-win-big-at-the-billboard-music-awards-20001206|title=Sisqo, Destiny's Child Win Big at the Billboard Music Awards}}</ref>\n*2000: Special Award for biggest one-week sales of an album ever by a female artist, ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]'', [[Britney Spears]]<ref name=\"2000bmas\" />\n*2001: Special Award for biggest one-week sales for an album in 2001: ''[[Celebrity (album)|Celebrity]]'', [[NSYNC]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=biggest-one-week-sales-for-an-album-in-2001-celebrity | title=Winners Database: Biggest one-week sales for an album in 2001 (\"Celebrity\")| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*2002: Special Award for 1982 album ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'', which spent more weeks at No. 1 (37) than any other album in the history of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]: [[Michael Jackson]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/?winnerKeyword=&winnerYear=&winnerCategory=special-billboard-award-michael-jackson-recognizing-his-1982-epic-album-thriller-which-spent-more-weeks-at-no-1-37-than-any-other-album-in-the-history-of-the-billboard-200 | title=Special Billboard Award: Michael Jackson \u2013 recognizing his 1982 Epic album \"Thriller\"| work=Billboard Music Awards | accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*2003: Special Hot 100 Award for Most Weeks at No. 1: [[Beyonc\u00e9]]{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Most wins==\nThe record for most ''Billboard'' Music Awards won is held by [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] with 27. The record for most ''Billboard'' Music Awards won by a female artist is held by [[Taylor Swift]] who has won 23 awards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboardmusicawards.com/winners-database/|title=Search All Time Winners}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Artist\n! Number of awards \n|-\n| 1.\n|[[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n|align=\"center| 27\n|-\n| 2.\n|[[Taylor Swift]]\n| align=center | 23\n|-\n| 3.\n| [[Justin Bieber]]                  \n| align=\"center| 20\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 4.\n| [[Garth Brooks]]\n| align=center rowspan=2| 19\n|-\n| [[Michael Jackson]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 5.\n| [[Adele]]\n| align=center rowspan=2 | 18\n|-\n| [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]\n|-\n| 6.\n|[[Whitney Houston]]\n| align=center | 16\n|-\n| 7.\n| [[Mariah Carey]]\n| align=center| 15\n|-\n| 8.\n| [[Beyonc\u00e9]]\n| align=center| 13\n|-\n| 9.\n| [[Rihanna]]\n| align=center| 12\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 10.\n| [[Carrie Underwood]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | 11\n|-\n|[[Janet Jackson]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 11.\n| [[Mary J. Blige]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 10\n|-\n|[[Eminem]]\n|-\n| [[Destiny's Child]]\n|-\n| [[50 Cent]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Broadcast==\nSince its inception (created by Rick Garson, Paul Flattery & Jim Yukich), the BMAs had been telecast on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network; however due to contractual expirations and other unforeseen circumstances, the awards were cancelled for 2007. Plans for a new version of the awards in 2008 (in association with [[AEG Live]]) fell through, and the BMAs were not held until 2011.\n\nOn February 17, 2011, ''Billboard'' announced that it would bring the BMAs back to television, moving from its original home on Fox to its new network, [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], on May 22, 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/tv-film/billboard-music-awards-to-air-live-from-1005040022.story|title=Billboard Music Awards To Air Live From Las Vegas On ABC May 22|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en}}</ref> A new award statuette was created by New York firm [[Society Awards]]. [[Dick Clark Productions]], which is co-owned with ''Billboard'', began producing the ceremony in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/6084674/the-billboard-music-awards-keep-bubbling|title=The Billboard Music Awards Keep Bubbling|work=Billboard|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en}}</ref> On November 28, 2017, it was announced that the ''Billboard'' Music Awards would be moving from ABC to [[NBC]] beginning in 2018 under a multi-year contract.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/billboard-music-awards-nbc-abc-1202624885/|title=Billboard Music Awards Move From ABC to NBC in Multi-Year Deal|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=2017-11-28|work=Variety|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 ceremony, originally scheduled for April 29, was postponed indefinitely on March 17 due to [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television|coronavirus-related]] public assembly concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/billboard-music-awards-be-rescheduled-1284816|title=Billboard Music Awards to Be Rescheduled|last=Nordyke|first=Kimberly|date=17 March 2020|work=[[Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Day\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Date\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Network\n! style=\"width:20%\" colspan=\"2\"| [[Nielsen ratings|Household rating]]\n! style=\"width:20%\" colspan=\"2\"| [[Nielsen ratings|18\u201349 rating]]\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Viewers<br />(in millions)\n! rowspan=\"2\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%\"| Rating\n! style=\"width:10%\"| Share\n! style=\"width:10%\"| Rating\n! style=\"width:10%\"| Share\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''[[1990 Billboard Music Awards|1990]]'''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Monday\n| December 10\n| rowspan=\"17\"| [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| 8.9\n| 14\n|\n|\n| 14.50\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{fact|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''[[1991 Billboard Music Awards|1991]]'''\n| December 9\n| 7.5\n| 11\n|\n|\n| 11.60\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{fact|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1992'''\n| rowspan=\"5\"| Wednesday\n| December 9\n| 9.4\n| 14\n|\n|\n| 15.00\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{fact|date=April 2020}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''1993'''\n| Decembe